00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:45.420
Senator Daniel K. Inouye was an
Olympian figure here in Washington

00:01:45.420 --> 00:01:47.650
and in his home state of Hawaii.

00:01:47.650 --> 00:01:52.640
Born in Honolulu on September 7,
1924, to Japanese American parents,

00:01:52.640 --> 00:01:56.910
he graduated from high school less
than six months after Pearl Harbor.

00:01:56.910 --> 00:02:00.350 position:56%
After the ban was lifted on Japanese
Americans serving their country,

00:02:00.350 --> 00:02:04.910
he enlisted in the Army and served
in the famous 442nd regiment

00:02:04.910 --> 00:02:09.020 position:56%
of the U.S. Army, a unit of Japanese
American soldiers who fought

00:02:09.020 --> 00:02:13.520
with extraordinary gallantry
in Italy, France, and Germany.

00:02:13.520 --> 00:02:17.310
On October 21, 1945, in the
war's final weeks in Europe,

00:02:17.310 --> 00:02:20.390
he was severely wounded
in battle after taking

00:02:20.390 --> 00:02:24.480
out two German machine gun
nests and lost his right arm.

00:02:24.480 --> 00:02:26.860
He returned home with a
distinguished service cross,

00:02:26.860 --> 00:02:28.820
bronze star medal,
two Purple Hearts,

00:02:28.820 --> 00:02:32.060
and 12 other medals and citations.

00:02:32.060 --> 00:02:34.920
He received extensive medical
treatment, and his commitment

00:02:34.920 --> 00:02:37.180
to bipartisanship may have stemmed

00:02:37.180 --> 00:02:40.080
from the lifelong friendship he
formed with another wounded veteran

00:02:40.080 --> 00:02:45.100
in the same hospital, the future
Senator Bob Dole of Kansas.

00:02:45.100 --> 00:02:48.400
After coming home, he graduated
from the University of Hawaii,

00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:51.990 position:56%
then law school, and became Hawaii's
first representative in 1959

00:02:51.990 --> 00:02:53.390
when Hawaii became a state.

00:02:53.390 --> 00:02:56.350
Three years later he
was elected senator,

00:02:56.350 --> 00:03:00.710 position:56%
part of a freshman class inspired by
the young President John F. Kennedy,

00:03:00.710 --> 00:03:02.010
including his brother,

00:03:02.010 --> 00:03:04.970
Edward Kennedy [inaudible]
and George McGovern.

00:03:04.970 --> 00:03:08.070 position:56%
He served for nearly half a century
in the Senate, leaving a rich legacy

00:03:08.070 --> 00:03:10.840
that includes the National Museum
of the Native American just

00:03:10.840 --> 00:03:13.180
down the street and
prominent service

00:03:13.180 --> 00:03:16.190
on the Senate Watergate committee,
the Senate Iran Contra Committee,

00:03:16.190 --> 00:03:18.350
and the Senate Appropriations
Committee,

00:03:18.350 --> 00:03:22.330
which he chaired from 2009 to 2012.

00:03:22.330 --> 00:03:25.910
He was awarded the Congressional
Medal of Honor on June 1, 2000,

00:03:25.910 --> 00:03:28.640
for his military service,
a day I was proud to be

00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:31.130
in the audience at the White House.

00:03:31.130 --> 00:03:33.900
After his death on
December 17, 2012,

00:03:33.900 --> 00:03:37.340
he was posthumously awarded the
Presidential Medal of Freedom,

00:03:37.340 --> 00:03:39.600
becoming the first senator
to receive both the Medal

00:03:39.600 --> 00:03:42.300
of Freedom and the Medal of Honor.

00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:45.310
Tonight the John W. Kluge Center
at the Library of Congress

00:03:45.310 --> 00:03:48.870
